Among the modes ‘quibus obligatio tollitur’ described by Gaius ia the commencement os an action, litis contestatio, which, isthe action were a iudicium legitimum, produced a quasi-novative effect, termed by the commentators novatio necessaria3 the very delivery ol the formula in the action by the praetorto the iudex extinguished the delendaut’s debr, and substituted lor it a new obligation‚ viz. the legal liability to be condemned il the plaintiff proved his case, Gaius lii. 180, 181. lt dif- lered, however, in its operation lrom novatio proper (novatio voluntaria), for it left the original obligation subsisting naturaliter, Dig. 12. 6. 60, and, as a consequence, did not destrny accessory rights, such as guaranties, hypothecs, ete, Dig. 46. 2. 29. Of this process-consumption, as it is called, there are still traces 111 the Corpus iuris, bnt the general rule under Justinian is that litis contestatio no longer extinguishes the cre· ditor's right, Bk. lv. 13. 10 inl, Cod. 3.1. 13. 2 and 5; 3.1o. 1. pr. It must indeed have ceased to extinguish it ipso iure with the disappearance ot' iudicia legitima under Diocletian, nn. 294 ; but now indeed it no longer enables it to be counteracted ope exceptionis; an obligatio is destroyed, not by the bringing of au action, but only by its adjudication‚ so that we cease to read of the exceptio rei in iudicium deductae, which is swallowed up in the exceptio rei iudicatae, Dig. 9. 44. 33 14 5. 4. 5: see on Bk. iv. 13. 51111. Novatio necessaria is also said by Gaius to be produced by judgment, sententia, res iudicata; sor its effecta which do not belong here, see Poste’s Gaius, p. 447.
